<div id="review_3854237214" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3854237214" />
    <a title="Katja" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/44594602-katja"><img alt="Katja" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1622146686p2/44594602.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3854237214?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katja" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katja" href="/user/show/44594602-katja">Katja</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19228131-historia-calamitatum">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3854237214&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3854237214" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2598525941613107812">Don’t usually log all the stuff I read for my course because typically they’re extracts for 200/400 page chunky books but this one was a nice little compact read! If you’re even slightly interested in medieval history and want to read the dramatic tale of one guy’s incredibly unfortunate life (intellectual enemies, a forbidden romance that ends in a convent, a castration, a book burning and many more fun things) this is the book to start with! <br/><br/>Also the letters of Abelard and Heloise, which direc</span>
  <span id="freeText2598525941613107812" style="display:none">Don’t usually log all the stuff I read for my course because typically they’re extracts for 200/400 page chunky books but this one was a nice little compact read! If you’re even slightly interested in medieval history and want to read the dramatic tale of one guy’s incredibly unfortunate life (intellectual enemies, a forbidden romance that ends in a convent, a castration, a book burning and many more fun things) this is the book to start with! <br /><br />Also the letters of Abelard and Heloise, which directly follow on from this piece by Abelard, are such a good read. I love parts of history, little stories like the one these letters tell, that only those who are interested or study the subject know about. They feel like a well kept yet also famous secret. <br /><br />Ew, that’s incredibly nerdy. What I’m saying is if you like medical history give this a read okay? Okay. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2598525941613107812" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


