    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2837654834" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2837654834" />
    <a title="Mjhancock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3897241-mjhancock"><img alt="Mjhancock" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2837654834?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mjhancock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mjhancock" href="/user/show/3897241-mjhancock">Mjhancock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781548969585" href="/book/show/35816039-historia-calamitatum">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=autobiographical">autobiographical</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=12th-c">12th-c</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2837654834" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8154897051718379228">Peter Abelard&apos;s 11th century account of his life and persecution is interesting, though not really enough for me to recommend it on that basis. Perhaps the book&apos;s biggest selling point is its relative brevity. My understanding is that Abelard is known for two things: his role as a frequently persecuted and controversial figure in Catholic church theology, and, much more significantly, his role as a famous Medieval lover in a doomed romance: he seduced his student Heloise, secretly married her wh</span>
  <span id="freeText8154897051718379228" style="display:none">Peter Abelard's 11th century account of his life and persecution is interesting, though not really enough for me to recommend it on that basis. Perhaps the book's biggest selling point is its relative brevity. My understanding is that Abelard is known for two things: his role as a frequently persecuted and controversial figure in Catholic church theology, and, much more significantly, his role as a famous Medieval lover in a doomed romance: he seduced his student Heloise, secretly married her when she discovered she was pregnant, and was subsequently castrated by her enraged uncle and his friends when they discovered the truth. I had no idea of either context; I stumbled on the book in a recent drive to read more nonfiction. Mission accomplished?<br /><br />It says a lot about Abelard's character that he spends far more time dwelling on his persecution for his intellectual claims than his castration. He comes off not particularly well based on his own words; he has a tendency towards self-aggrandizement that makes it difficult to take seriously either his own arguments or his accounts of his opponents. This particular edition (with translation by Henry Adams Bellows and introduction by Ralph Adams Cram) provides some absolute essential context by relating his story in brief, along with the massive influence of the Catholic Church in this era. It's immensely useful (probably moreso than the main text), but it still feels more like a snapshot in time than a detailed history. Still, for a brief dip into history, it serves its purpose.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8154897051718379228" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

